<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="85" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="85">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="85">
On wood of deciduous tree, in forest dominated by 
<taxonomicName family="Rosaceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Moraceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="family">Moraceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Lauraceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="family">Lauraceae</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName family="Theaceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="family">Theaceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="86" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="85">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="86" pageId="10" pageNumber="85">
Only one specimen representing 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. salmonea" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="salmonea">T. salmonea</taxonomicName>
formed a distinct clade closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. taiwanensis" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">T. taiwanensis</taxonomicName>
with 96.8%-98.3% sequence identities in D1/D2 domain and 95.4%-96.6% in ITS region, respectively. The affinity of 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. salmonea" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="salmonea">T. salmonea</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. taiwanensis" pageId="10" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">T. taiwanensis</taxonomicName>
<pageBreakToken pageId="11" pageNumber="86" start="start">lacked</pageBreakToken>
high support by the coalescent-based method (Fig. 1). 
<taxonomicName class="Tremellomycetes" family="Tremellaceae" genus="Tremella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Tremella salmonea" order="Tremellales" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="salmonea">Tremella salmonea</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. taiwanensis" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">T. taiwanensis</taxonomicName>
in its larger basidia (31.0-38.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
29.0-37.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. salmonea" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="salmonea">T. salmonea</taxonomicName>
vs 23.0-29.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
22.0-27.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. taiwanensis" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">T. taiwanensis</taxonomicName>
) and basidiospores (16.0-22.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
15.0-20.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. salmonea" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="salmonea">T. salmonea</taxonomicName>
vs 14.0-18.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="×14.0–">x14.0-</normalizedToken>
20.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. taiwanensis" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">T. taiwanensis</taxonomicName>
). In addition, hyphae-like conidiogenous cells and dikaryotic conidia were observed in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. salmonea" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="salmonea">T. salmonea</taxonomicName>
compared to monokaryotic conidia produced from apex of sterigmata (
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, CJ" journalOrPublisher="Bibliotheca Mycologica" pageId="15" pageNumber="90" pagination="1 - 225" title="Morphological and molecular studies in the genus Tremella." volume="174" year="1998">Chen 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Swollen cells were located in the hymenium in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. salmonea" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="salmonea">T. salmonea</taxonomicName>
whereas they were absent in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. taiwanensis" pageId="11" pageNumber="86" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">T. taiwanensis</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, CJ" journalOrPublisher="Bibliotheca Mycologica" pageId="15" pageNumber="90" pagination="1 - 225" title="Morphological and molecular studies in the genus Tremella." volume="174" year="1998">Chen 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
